<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Bongamandla, known as Bongstar K, is now sharing his soothing music!He told Daily Sun music helped him accept his juvenile arthritis diagnosis. “I was nine when I suddenly started getting pains in my joints,” he said. “It only became worse and I ended up in a wheelchair.”He said they tried all sorts of help for him to regain movement. “I was referred to the special needs school Ezibeleni Primary in Katlehong, Ekurhuleni,” he said. “I played lots of music while there to escape the fear of the unknown.” He said people need to accept themselves as they are, otherwise they won’t live positive lives. He has two singles, Ngihlawulile and Qaphela, under his belt. He’s in studio recording a full album, Inzalabantu, to be released soon.“It’s a thank you album to all the mothers of Mzansi,” he said. “I salute my mum Siphiwe Khumalo (78) for raising me. “She never gave up on me, took care of me, and would never hide me. She taught me love.” He’s been a wheelchair rugby player since 1998. He represented Mzansi in 2009 in Christchurch, New Zealand, while playing for the national wheelchair rugby team.He’s studying business administration at Sparrow FET College in Sophiatown, Joburg. “I want to empower myself to get a job,” he said.